    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Educational Deep Dive: Raster Images (JPG) vs. Document Formats (PDF)</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Why not just send a folder full of JPGs? To understand why PDF is superior for documents, we have to look at the difference between a <strong>Raster</strong> image and a <strong>Document</strong> format. 
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        JPGs and PNGs are raster formats, meaning they are just a grid of colored pixels. When you send 10 JPGs, the computer sees them as 10 separate, independent pieces of art. A <strong>PDF (Portable Document Format)</strong>, however, is a container. It doesn't just hold the pixels; it holds the <em>structure</em>. It keeps pages in order, preserves the "physical" layout of a document, and allows for text search and metadata that raw images simply can't handle.
    </p>

