    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Why is PDF Better Than JPG?</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        You might be wondering: Why go through the trouble of making a PDF at all? Why not just send the pictures?
    </p>
    <ul style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li><strong>Universal Compatibility:</strong> A PDF (Portable Document Format) looks the exact same on every
            single device. Whether your friend opens it on an old Android phone, a brand-new laptop, or a library
            computer, the formatting will never break.</li>
        <li><strong>Professionalism:</strong> If you are submitting an assignment to a teacher or a document to a
            business, a single PDF looks incredibly professional. A zip file full of randomly named images (like
            IMG_9483.JPG) looks disorganized.</li>
        <li><strong>Easy Printing:</strong> Try printing 10 separate images from your phone; you will likely waste a lot
            of paper and ink. A PDF is inherently designed for printing, ensuring your images fit perfectly onto
            standard paper sizes.</li>
    </ul>

